// Function to check if Box 1 can be the special box
bool can_be_box1(long long A, long long B, long long C, long long D) {
    // To end up in Box 1, the final product must be <= -1.
    // This requires an odd number of negative factors.
    // The only way to get a negative product is to have an odd number of initial negative toys.
    // Initial negative toys are from Box 1 and Box 2.
    // So, (A + B) must be odd.

    // If A+B is even, the final product will always be positive (or zero, but fun values are real).
    if ((A + B) % 2 == 0) {
        return false;
    }

    // If A+B is odd, we can always arrange for the final product to be negative.
    // Now we need to ensure it can be <= -1.
    // Consider the absolute value of the product.
    // If we have at least one toy in Box 1 or Box 4, we can make the absolute value large.
    // If A > 0 or D > 0, we can always make the absolute value >= 1.
    // Example: if A=1, B=0, C=0, D=0, then the toy is in Box 1.
    // If A=0, B=1, C=0, D=0, then the toy is in Box 2.
    // If A=0, B=1, C=1, D=0, product can be in Box 2 (e.g., -0.5 * 0.5 = -0.25).
    // If A=0, B=1, C=0, D=1, product can be in Box 1 (e.g., -0.5 * 3 = -1.5).

    // If A+B is odd:
    // If A > 0 or D > 0, we have at least one toy with absolute value >= 1.
    // We can multiply all toys with absolute value < 1 first (from B and C).
    // The product of these will be in (0, 1) or (-1, 0).
    // Let this intermediate product be P_small.
    // If P_small is positive, it's in (0,1). If negative, in (-1,0).
    // Then we multiply P_small with toys from A and D.
    // If we have any toy from A or D, we can make the final product's absolute value large enough.
    // For example, if we have a toy with value -3 (from A) and another with value 3 (from D).
    // We can multiply all other toys to get some value P_other.
    // Then multiply P_other by -3 and 3.
    // If A > 0 or D > 0, we can always achieve a product with absolute value >= 1.
    // Example: if A=1, B=1, C=0, D=0. (A+B=2, even) -> false.
    // Example: if A=1, B=0, C=0, D=1. (A+B=1, odd). We have -3 and 3. Product -9. Box 1. Ya.
    // Example: if A=0, B=1, C=0, D=1. (A+B=1, odd). We have -0.5 and 3. Product -1.5. Box 1. Ya.

    // The only case where the absolute value might be stuck below 1 is if all initial toys have absolute values less than 1.
    // This means A=0 and D=0.
    // If A=0 and D=0, then all toys are from Box 2 or Box 3.
    // Their absolute values are all in (0, 1).
    // The product of any number of such toys will always have an absolute value in (0, 1).
    // So, if A=0 and D=0, the final product will always be in Box 2 or Box 3.
    // Therefore, if A=0 and D=0, Box 1 cannot be the special box.

    // Combining these:
    // Box 1 can be special if (A+B) is odd AND (A > 0 or D > 0).
    // This simplifies to: (A+B) is odd AND NOT (A=0 and D=0).
    return ((A + B) % 2 == 1) && (A > 0 || D > 0);
}

// Function to check if Box 2 can be the special box
bool can_be_box2(long long A, long long B, long long C, long long D) {
    // To end up in Box 2, the final product must be in (-1, 0).
    // This requires an odd number of negative factors.
    // So, (A + B) must be odd.

    // If A+B is even, the final product will always be positive.
    if ((A + B) % 2 == 0) {
        return false;
    }

    // If A+B is odd, we can always arrange for the final product to be negative.
    // Now we need to ensure it can be in (-1, 0).
    // This means the absolute value of the product must be in (0, 1).
    // This is possible if all initial toys have absolute values less than 1.
    // This means A=0 and D=0.
    // If A=0 and D=0, then all toys are from Box 2 or Box 3.
    // Their absolute values are all in (0, 1).
    // The product of any number of such toys will always have an absolute value in (0, 1).
    // So, if A=0 and D=0, and (A+B) is odd, the product will be in Box 2.

    // What if A > 0 or D > 0? Can we still make it end up in Box 2?
    // Yes, if we have at least one toy from Box 2 or Box 3 (i.e., B+C > 0).
    // If B+C > 0, we can pick a toy from Box 2 or Box 3 (e.g., 0.5 or -0.5).
    // We can make all other toys multiply to a very large or very small absolute value.
    // For example, if we have a toy with value -0.5 (from B).
    // We can multiply all other toys to get a product P_other.
    // If P_other is very large (e.g., 1000), then -0.5 * 1000 = -500 (Box 1).
    // If P_other is very small (e.g., 0.001), then -0.5 * 0.001 = -0.0005 (Box 2).
    // The key is that we can choose the *values* of the toys.
    // If A+B is odd, we can always make the product negative.
    // If there is at least one toy in B or C (B+C > 0), we can choose its value to be very close to 0 (e.g., -0.0001 or 0.0001).
    // Then, no matter what the product of the other N-1 toys is (let it be P_rest),
    // the final product will be P_rest * (very small value).
    // This will result in an absolute value very close to 0, thus in Box 2 or Box 3.
    // Since A+B is odd, the sign will be negative, so it will be in Box 2.

    // So, if A+B is odd:
    // If B+C > 0, we can make it Box 2.
    // If B+C = 0, then all toys are from A or D.
    // If A+B is odd, and B=0, then A must be odd.
    // If B+C=0, then C=0. So all toys are from A or D.
    // If A is odd, and D can be anything.
    // Example: A=1, D=0. Product is in Box 1.
    // Example: A=1, D=1. Product is in Box 1.
    // Example: A=3, D=0. Product is in Box 1.
    // If B+C=0, and A+B is odd, then A must be odd.
    // In this case, all toys are from A or D.
    // All toys have absolute value >= 1.
    // The product of such toys will always have absolute value >= 1.
    // So, if B+C=0, it cannot be Box 2.

    // Combining these:
    // Box 2 can be special if (A+B) is odd AND (B > 0 or C > 0).
    // This simplifies to: (A+B) is odd AND NOT (A=0 and D=0).
    // Wait, this is the same condition as Box 1. Let's re-evaluate.

    // Let's consider the total number of toys N = A+B+C+D.
    // If N=1:
    // If A=1, Box 1.
    // If B=1, Box 2.
    // If C=1, Box 3.
    // If D=1, Box 4.
    // So if B=1 and A=C=D=0, Box 2 is special. This satisfies (A+B)%2==1 and (B>0 or C>0).

    // If A+B is odd:
    // We can always make the final product negative.
    // To make it in Box 2 (i.e., absolute value < 1):
    // We need to be able to choose initial values such that the product's absolute value is < 1.
    // This is possible if there is at least one toy in Box 2 or Box 3 (B+C > 0).
    // If B+C > 0, we can assign a value very close to 0 (e.g., 0.0001 or -0.0001) to one of these toys.
    // The product of all other N-1 toys will be some value P_rest.
    // The final product will be P_rest * (very small value), which will have an absolute value < 1.
    // Since A+B is odd, the sign will be negative. So it ends up in Box 2.
    // This works unless B+C = 0.
    // If B+C = 0, then all toys are from A or D.
    // If A+B is odd, and B=0, then A must be odd.
    // So, if B+C=0, and A is odd, all toys are from A or D.
    // All toys have absolute value >= 1. Their product will have absolute value >= 1.
    // So, if B+C=0, it cannot be Box 2.

    // So, Box 2 can be special if (A+B) is odd AND (B > 0 or C > 0).
    return ((A + B) % 2 == 1) && (B > 0 || C > 0);
}

// Function to check if Box 3 can be the special box
bool can_be_box3(long long A, long long B, long long C, long long D) {
    // To end up in Box 3, the final product must be in (0, 1).
    // This requires an even number of negative factors.
    // So, (A + B) must be even.

    // If A+B is odd, the final product will always be negative.
    if ((A + B) % 2 == 1) {
        return false;
    }

    // If A+B is even, we can always arrange for the final product to be positive.
    // Now we need to ensure it can be in (0, 1).
    // This means the absolute value of the product must be in (0, 1).
    // This is possible if there is at least one toy in Box 2 or Box 3 (B+C > 0).
    // Similar logic to Box 2: if B+C > 0, we can assign a value very close to 0 (e.g., 0.0001 or -0.0001)
    // to one of these toys.
    // The product of all other N-1 toys will be some value P_rest.
    // The final product will be P_rest * (very small value), which will have an absolute value < 1.
    // Since A+B is even, the sign will be positive. So it ends up in Box 3.
    // This works unless B+C = 0.
    // If B+C = 0, then all toys are from A or D.
    // If A+B is even, and B=0, then A must be even.
    // So, if B+C=0, and A is even, all toys are from A or D.
    // All toys have absolute value >= 1. Their product will have absolute value >= 1.
    // So, if B+C=0, it cannot be Box 3.

    // So, Box 3 can be special if (A+B) is even AND (B > 0 or C > 0).
    return ((A + B) % 2 == 0) && (B > 0 || C > 0);
}

// Function to check if Box 4 can be the special box
bool can_be_box4(long long A, long long B, long long C, long long D) {
    // To end up in Box 4, the final product must be >= 1.
    // This requires an even number of negative factors.
    // So, (A + B) must be even.

    // If A+B is odd, the final product will always be negative.
    if ((A + B) % 2 == 1) {
        return false;
    }

    // If A+B is even, we can always arrange for the final product to be positive.
    // Now we need to ensure it can be >= 1.
    // This is possible if there is at least one toy in Box 1 or Box 4 (A+D > 0).
    // If A+D > 0, we have at least one toy with absolute value >= 1.
    // We can assign a value very large (e.g., -1000 or 1000) to one of these toys.
    // The product of all other N-1 toys will be some value P_rest.
    // The final product will be P_rest * (very large value), which will have an absolute value >= 1.
    // Since A+B is even, the sign will be positive. So it ends up in Box 4.
    // This works unless A+D = 0.
    // If A+D = 0, then all toys are from Box 2 or Box 3.
    // All toys have absolute value in (0, 1).
    // The product of any number of such toys will always have an absolute value in (0, 1).
    // So, if A+D=0, it cannot be Box 4.

    // So, Box 4 can be special if (A+B) is even AND (A > 0 or D > 0).
    return ((A + B) % 2 == 0) && (A > 0 || D > 0);
}

